Here is the complete conceptual breakdown of your project.

Phase 1: The Database (The Foundation)
To make a cinema system work, your database needs specific "tables" or "collections" that talk to each other. Your professors will likely ask about relationships.

Here is what your system is almost certainly storing:

Users: Stores user details (Name, Email, Password, Role: Admin vs. Customer).

Movies: Stores movie details (Title, Duration, Poster, Language).

Screens/Theaters: Stores the physical rooms (e.g., Screen 1 has 100 seats).

Shows/Schedules: This is the most important link! A "Show" connects a Movie to a Screen at a specific Time.

Bookings/Tickets: Connects a User to specific Seats for a specific Show.

Phase 2: The Admin Flow (Backend Management)
Before a customer can book a ticket, the admin has to set the system up. Your code will have a section (likely an Admin Dashboard) that handles CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete).

Admin logs in.

Admin creates a Movie.

Admin creates a Screen and defines how many seats it has.

Admin schedules a Show (e.g., Batman playing on Screen 1 at 8:00 PM).

Phase 3: The User Flow (The Booking Journey)
This is what the customer sees. When you explain your project, walk the professors through this exact journey:

Browsing: The user fetches a list of available Movies and Shows from the database.

Seat Layout: When a user clicks a Show, the system checks the database to see which seats are "Available", "Locked", or "Booked" and renders a visual grid on the frontend.

Selection: The user clicks a seat.

Checkout & Payment: The user pays, and the system generates a ticket/receipt.

Phase 4: The Most Important Concept - Seat Locking (Concurrency)
Professors love asking about this. They will ask: "What happens if User A and User B try to book Seat #12 at the exact same millisecond?"

This is called a Race Condition. Here is how your code likely solves it:

The Temporary Lock: When User A clicks Seat #12 and goes to the payment page, the database updates the status of Seat #12 from "Available" to "Locked" (or "Pending").

The Timer: A timestamp is attached. User A is given, for example, 5 minutes to complete the payment.

User B's View: Because the database says "Locked," if User B tries to click Seat #12, the system will say "Seat is currently reserved by another user."

Success or Failure: * If User A pays, the status changes to "Booked" permanently.

If User A cancels or the 5-minute timer runs out, the system automatically changes the status back to "Available" so User B can grab it.

